# Version 1 — Architectural Redesign

> *We didn't scrap Version 1 because it failed. We redesigned it because we outgrew it.*

---

## Why a Redesign Was Necessary

Version 1 proved the concept worked. Automations ran. KPIs calculated. Tasks were tracked.

But as usage grew, one truth became impossible to ignore — the system was built around what we needed *that week*, not what we needed *long term*. Every new feature was bolted on top of the last one. The foundation wasn't designed to carry the weight we were putting on it.

There was no separation between data and logic. No room for external integrations. No way to scale without rebuilding anyway.

So instead of patching a system that was structurally limited, we made the decision to redesign from the ground up — keeping everything we learned, throwing away everything that was holding us back.

---

## What Changed and Why

### From One Sheet to Layered Architecture

**Before:** Everything lived on one sheet. Raw inputs, calculated KPIs, automation outputs — all mixed together in 26 columns.

**After:** Three distinct layers, each with a single responsibility.

```
Layer 1 — Data Input
Raw task data only. No calculations. No formatting logic.
This is the single source of truth.

Layer 2 — Automation Engine
Google Apps Script handles all logic.
Timestamps, status triggers, ID generation, validation.
Nothing runs manually.

Layer 3 — Dashboard & Analytics
Pulls from Layer 1. Displays KPIs, charts, and insights.
Never touches raw data directly.
```

**Why this matters:** When each layer does one job, fixing a bug doesn't break everything else. Adding a new feature means extending one layer, not rewriting three.

---

### From Flat Columns to Structured Data Model

**Before:** Columns were added as needs emerged. No planned structure. Mixed data types in the same rows.

**After:** Data model planned before a single formula was written.

```
Core Task Fields (Identity)
├── Task ID (auto-generated, category-coded)
├── Task Name
├── Category
├── Priority
└── Status

Time Fields (Tracking)
├── Start Date (auto-populated)
├── Due Date (manual)
└── Completion Date (locked once set)

Performance Fields (Measurement)
├── Duration
├── Estimated vs Actual
├── Efficiency Score
└── Overdue Status

Goal Alignment Fields (NEW in V2)
├── Linked Goal
├── Mind Map Category
└── Progress Toward Goal
```

**Why this matters:** A planned data model means every field has a purpose. Nothing is duplicated. Everything connects.

---

### From Fragile Triggers to Reliable Automation

**Before:** `onEdit` triggers with no error handling. Status values typed manually. Timestamps overwritten on re-edits.

**After:** Automation built to handle real human behaviour.

- Status values controlled by dropdowns — no typos, no silent failures
- Completion timestamps locked after first write — re-opening a task preserves history
- Error handling built into every script from the start
- Automations tested against edge cases, not just ideal paths

---

### From Standalone Tracker to Goal-Connected System

**Before:** Tasks existed in isolation. No connection to bigger goals. Busy but not necessarily productive.

**After:** Every task connects back to a goal through the mind map structure.

```
Your Goal
    └── Category
          └── Subcategory
                └── Task
```

This means every completed task shows visible progress toward something that actually matters. Not just a checkbox. A step forward.

